<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<handout>
  <title>Worksheet 1.1, Systems of Linear Equations</title>

  <ul marker="">
    <li workspace="2in">
      <p>(1) &#160; Indicate whether the statements are true or false.</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>If a linear system has more equations than unknowns, then the system cannot have a unique solution.</p></li>
        <li><p>If a linear system has more unknowns than equations, then the system cannot have a unique solution.</p></li>
      </ol>
      <p>Before moving on - what strategies does your TA(s) recommend that students can use to approach true/false questions?</p>
    </li>

    <li workspace="4in">
      <p>(2) &#160; For what values of <m>A</m> and <m>B</m>, if any, does the system have each behavior below?</p>
      <ol marker="(a)">
        <li><p>an infinite number of solutions</p></li>
        <li><p>no solutions</p></li>
        <li><p>exactly one solution</p></li>
      </ol>

      <p>
        <me>
        \begin{aligned}
          x_1 + 2x_2 \amp= 1 \\
          A x_1 + B x_2 \amp= 2
        \end{aligned}
        </me>
      </p>

      <p>
        For the case where there are an infinite number of solutions, sketch the set of solutions.
        The sketch must have labeled axes, and the solution set should be drawn as a line without arrows.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li workspace="1in">
      <p>(3) &#160; From your TA’s perspective, what strategies do they recommend to ensure success in a college‑level linear algebra course? What strategies worked for them?</p>
      <p>This worksheet is intentionally shorter to allow time for course and studio organization.</p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</handout>